		{ value: '170,746', label: 'lives lost to suicide in 2024 — about one every three minutes' },
		{ value: '33.5%', label: 'of those suicides were driven by family problems — the leading cause' },
		{ value: '34.7%', label: 'of households still lack clean cooking fuel; 1 in 4 lack proper sanitation' },
		{ value: '7.6%', label: 'of suicides were linked to drug or alcohol addiction' },
		{ value: '10,546', label: 'farmers and farm laborers died by suicide — debt a major driver' },
	]}
	painsBodyHtml={`<p>Daily-wage earners make up the largest share of those lost to suicide &mdash; the people working hardest simply to survive. Debt drives farmers to despair; addiction fractures homes; and family breakdown, now the number-one cause of suicide, reaches into marriages and across generations. Divorce, long among the world&rsquo;s lowest, is climbing sharply in India&rsquo;s cities.</p><p>These are not abstract numbers. They are fathers without work, mothers without rest, sons and daughters without hope. India does not need another distant authority to obey &mdash; it needs a Father who draws near.</p>`}
	painsSources={[
		{ label: 'UNDP/NITI Aayog MPI 2024', url: 'https://hdr.undp.org/sites/default/files/Country-Profiles/MPI2024/IND.pdf' },
